{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488708"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:53:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:53:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"513"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/513"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.01,0.07,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32144"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/513"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17817"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"1409"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26892"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32144"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents with an episode of blurring of vision in his left eye. This lasted about ten minutes and then normal vision returned. A similar episode occurred one month earlier. He has a history of ischaemic heart disease with a drug eluting stent inserted two years ago, and hyperlipidaemia and hypertension. On examination, he has a normal visual acuity, no relative afferent pupillary defect and a full range of extraocular movements. His peripheral neurological exam is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Migrainous aura","Paroxysmal atrial fibrillation","Temporal lobe tumour","Giant cell arteritis","Carotid artery plaque"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with two episodes of visual blurring in the past month which lasted for minutes and self resolved. This is consistent with amaurosis fugax which occurs secondary to ischaemia in either the retina or optic nerve. The most common cause of amaurosis fugax is ipsilateral \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid artery plaque\u003C/strong\u003E with secondary thromboembolism to the central or branch retinal arteries. Other potential, but less likely causes, include cardioembolic sources e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E, and giant cell arteritis. \u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause amaurosis fugax in approximately 30% of patients prior to causing permanent visual loss. These episodes typically begin 8 days prior to permanent visual loss and are essential to pick up and treat in order to prevent permanent visual loss; headache and jaw claudication should raise suspicion. However, in this patient, given his past vascular history, a carotid artery plaque is the most likely cause of his presentation. A \u003Cstrong\u003Emigrainous aura\u003C/strong\u003E can produce a number of visual symptoms including flashing or zigzag lights, however these are usually bilateral and associated with other neurologic findings such as headaches. A \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporal lobe tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to cause amaurosis fugax and is more likely to present with neurologic complaints such as seizures, olfactory disturbances, amnesia and aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this patient does have carotid artery stenosis and this is the presumed source of the problem, that patient should be started on dual antiplatelet therapy promptly. If the degree of stenosis exceeds 80%, the patient should be referred for a vascular surgery opinion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The most common cause of amaurosis fugax is ipsilateral carotid artery plaque."],"references":["Bidot S, Biotti D. Transient monocular blindness: Vascular causes and differential diagnoses. J Fr Ophtalmol. 2018 Apr;41(4):e129-e136."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17817"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17817"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-03T14:48:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T14:14:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"513"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32144"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descripti